<p>Once you have your <a href="/blog/2019/2019-06-15/post/">MariaDB (MySQL alternative)</a> instance up and running, it would be a good idea to automate backing up your important databases. In this post I will cover performing a simple daily backup of your databases using <a href="https://mariadb.com/kb/en/mariadb-dumpmysqldump/">mysqldump</a>.</p>
<h2 id="create-mycnf">Create &quot;.my.cnf&quot;</h2>
<p>To make your backups easier I would suggest creating a <code>.my.cnf</code> file in your CRON users home directory. When <code>mysqldump</code> runs it will search for the current users' <code>.my.cnf</code> file to load additional settings (e.g. DB credentials) allowing you to omit them from the CRON jobs command.</p>
<p>To create the .my.cnf file, log in as the desired user and run the below command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo nano ~/.my.cnf
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Add the following to the file making sure to replace the <code>&lt;USER&gt;</code> and <code>&lt;PASS&gt;</code> placeholders with your credentials.</p>
{% highlight "ini" %}
[mysqldump]
host = 127.0.0.1
port = 3306
user = <USER>
password = <PASS>
{% endhighlight %}

<h2 id="testing-mysqldump">Testing mysqldump</h2>
<p>Before continuing it would be a good idea to make sure that mysqldump is able to read your configuration file and connect to your local database instance.</p>
<p>In my case I would like to create a daily backup of my CleanHome database, to create the backup I would run the following command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
mysqldump CleanHome > "CleanHome-$(date '+%F').sql"
{% endhighlight %}

<p>If everything works as expected a backup file should appear in your current working directory.</p>
<img src="./001.png" alt="" />
<h2 id="creating-the-cron-job">Creating the CRON job</h2>
<p>Next we need to register a daily CRON job to automatically run our mysqldump command. The easiest way to do this would be to make use of the crontab command (choosing basic if prompted):</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
crontab -e
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Add your backup command at the end of the file, in my case I added this:</p>
{% highlight "text" %}
00 22 * * * mysqldump --databases CleanHome > "/home/niemandr/CleanHome-$(date '+\%F').sql"
{% endhighlight %}

<blockquote>
<p><strong>Note</strong>: you need to escape special characters with an &quot;&quot; (e.g. <code>\%F</code> in the date command). You can use <a href="https://crontab.guru/#00_22_*_*_*">crontab.guru</a> to help build your CRON expression.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Close the text editor making sure to save your changes.</p>
<p>You have successfully created your backup job!</p>
<h2 id="troubleshooting">Troubleshooting</h2>
<p>Below are some helpful tips for troubleshooting a failing CRON job.</p>
<h3 id="reload-all-cron-jobs">Reload all CRON jobs</h3>
<p>Some linux distributions may not automatically refresh jobs when a change has been made (Ubuntu does BTW), if your job is not running you could try reloading with this command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
sudo service cron reload
{% endhighlight %}

<h3 id="tail-your-system-log-file">Tail your system log file</h3>
<p>You can troubleshoot a failing job by looking at your systems log file (on Ubuntu <code>/var/log/syslog</code>) for any entries containing your CRON job, in our case you can use the following command:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
cat /var/log/syslog | grep mysqldump
{% endhighlight %}

<p>Ideally you can schedule the job to run on the next min and tail your systems log file:</p>
{% highlight "shell" %}
tail -f /var/log/syslog
{% endhighlight %}

<p>If you are lucky you may see the reason for the failure logged.</p>
